## Development Standards

### WordPress Coding Standards

- Follow [WordPress PHP Coding Standards](https://developer.wordpress.org/coding-standards/wordpress-coding-standards/php/)
- Follow [WordPress JavaScript Coding Standards](https://developer.wordpress.org/coding-standards/wordpress-coding-standards/javascript/)
- Use tabs for indentation (PHP and JS)
- Maximum line length: 100 characters (soft limit)

### Naming Conventions

- Functions: `[prefix_]function_name`
- Classes: `[Prefix_]Class_Name` or `[Prefix]\Namespace\ClassName`
- Constants: `[PREFIX_]CONSTANT_NAME`
- Hooks: `[prefix_]/hook-name` or `[prefix_]_hook_name`

### Security Requirements

**Always:**
- Sanitize all input: `sanitize_text_field()`, `absint()`, `sanitize_email()`, etc.
- Escape all output: `esc_html()`, `esc_attr()`, `esc_url()`, etc.
- Verify nonces AND check capabilities for all admin actions
- Use `$wpdb->prepare()` for all database queries with user input

**Never:**
- Trust `$_GET`, `$_POST`, `$_REQUEST` without sanitization
- Echo user input without escaping
- Use `eval()` or similar dangerous functions

### i18n Requirements

- Wrap all user-facing strings in translation functions
- Use text domain: `[text-domain]`
- Include translator comments for complex strings

```php
__( 'Text', '[text-domain]' );
_e( 'Text', '[text-domain]' );
/* translators: %s: user name */
sprintf( __( 'Hello, %s', '[text-domain]' ), $name );
```

